<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_6.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_6.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>IRONMAN</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>19 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
What's Christmas without a bit of Humbug? Christmas 1990 didn't mark
the end of the golden era - the era ended well before then!
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The hype cycle had lost its sparkle and had become disappointingly
cynical. Amongst the big names for that year were <i>Teenage Mutant Hero
Turtles</i> and <i>Gazza</i> - two high-profile franchises, the latter of which
made little sense to me. <i>Gazza</i> was even riding high in the charts with
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/qgDKtLPp46s&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/qgDKtLPp46s&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Only You / Flying Pickets</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Beautiful - a Christmas song which brings a tear to your eye, and was a nice distraction from the miners strikes of the time. <b><i>(3:17)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qgDKtLPp46s" target="qgDKtLPp46s">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

songs such as "Fog On The Tyne", and even had an album out for
Christmas. It even sold well. Sequels became inevitable, and <i>Robocop 2</i>
and <i>Chase HQ 2</i> arrived, made a brief splash, and then were more or
less instantly forgotten.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/SzzxZRXJPQg&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/SzzxZRXJPQg&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Christmas 1983 Adverts</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">I love the adverts in the run-up to Christmas, so here's a few from 1983. See if you can spot a young Mel Smith and Hugh Laurie... <b><i>(8:28)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SzzxZRXJPQg" target="SzzxZRXJPQg">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
By this time I had already switched my Spectrum 48k+ for one of the
doomed SAM Coupes. My SAM seemed to have some sort of spiritual link
with it's manufacturer - when MGT went under, so did my SAM. Then
SAMCo took over, my SAM got repaired, only to fail again when SAMCo
did. The long and the short of it was that I was restricted to 48K
games, SAM PD stuff, and the rather basic SAM <i>Defenders Of The Earth</i>.
Which was rather unfortunate as the Spectrum full price market was
switching over to 128K-only titles, so the prospect of an Ocean-free
Christmas wasn't exactly thrilling me at that time.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;However, one game stood out for me purely because of the YS MegaPreview: <i>Ivan "Ironman" Stewart's Super Off-Road Racer</i>, and not
just because it has one of the longest names for a Spectrum game ever.
Sure, a <i>SuperSprint</i> clone is a <i>SuperSprint</i> clone, but this had very
<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=200 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d6_ironmanyspreview.png" target="ironmanyspreview.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d6_ironmanyspreview_small.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=222></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Who says computer games weren't educational?</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
sharp colourful graphics, tough courses, and lots of pseudo-3D bumps
and ramps together with a smart physics engine that made the game a
lot more fun to play. And it came out on 48K!
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The playable demo for it didn't help its cause: it didn't work for me!
I'd get the front menu, and that's as far as it would go. Turns out that the demo would only work on one particular version of the Spectrum +2. But it
didn't matter - the moment the great reviews came out for it was the
moment I bought it and I never looked back.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The game's a damn fine one, but eventually I discovered it had a
single flaw to do with lastability. Since I played the game to death,
I became very very good at it. Suddenly I was playing through all the
courses, forwards, backwards, with tougher opponents, and I'd soup up
my truck to the max before the game turned into one giant endurance
test.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It turned out that the only way to end a game was to turn the machine
off! But boy was the game challenging whilst you were getting to grips
with it - if only it had a few more difficulty levels and it would
have become an all-time classic. As it is, it's merely the best
top-down driving game available for the Spectrum.
